<DOC><DOCNO> AP881121-0296 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-21-88 1434EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     11-21 0319</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0331</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Falls On Bush Remarks About Deficit, Gold Lower</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5:30 p.m. EST</NOTE><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The U.S. dollar fell against all major currenciesin European trading Monday amid continued anxiety about the Americanbudget deficit. Gold prices declined.   Currency dealers said the dollar was hurt by remarks fromPresident-elect George Bush reaffirming that he won't raise taxes tonarrow the huge gap. At issue is whether Bush and theDemocratic-controlled U.S. Congress can agree on spending cutsneeded to trim the deficit.   Dealers also reported a lack of central-bank intervention Mondayto prop up the dollar's exchange rate as there had been last week.One trader said the dollar cannot maintain its current exchangerates without central bank buying.   The Canadian dollar gained more than two cents in London againstthe U.S. dollar on the heels of Saturday's opinion polls predictingvictory in Monday's Canadian general election for Prime MinisterBrian Mulroney's Conservatives.   In London late Monday, one British pound cost $1.8175, moreexpensive for buyers than Friday's late $1.8160.   Other late rates compared with late rates Friday: 1.7305 WestGerman marks, down from 1.7360; 1.4575 Swiss francs, down from1.4585; 5.9305 French francs, down from 5.9340; 1.9550 Dutchguilders, down from 1.9610; 1,288.62 Italian lire, down from1,293.75; and 1.2117 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2343.   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business daybegains, the dollar closed at 122.52 Japanese yen, up from 122.40late Friday. But in late London trading the dollar fell lower to122.20 yen.   Gold bullion closed in London, the major European market, at$416.75 a troy ounce, down from $417.75 bid late Friday. The lateprice in Zurich was $416.50 an ounce, down from $417.80.   Gold closed in Hong Kong at $418.79 an ounce, down from $419.12.   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $6.04 a troy ounce,down from $6.09.</TEXT></DOC>